6","1641":"1641","1585":"1585","1552":"1552","12 February 1646":"12. februar 1646","12 Feb 1646":"12. februar 1646","11 Dec 1552":"11. december 1552","02 Mar 1609":"2. marts 1609","1603":"1603","1559":"1559","Lochinver, Sutherland, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Lochinver, Sutherland, Skotland, United Kingdom","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Edinburgh, Skotland, United Kingdom","Lochinver, Sutherland, Scotland":"Lochinver, Sutherland, Skotland","Kirkland,Kilmairis,Stirling,Ayers, Scottland":"Stirling, Western Australia, Australien","County Donegal, Ireland":"County Donegal, Irland"},"nl":{"11 Dec 1552–12 Feb 1646":"11 december 1552–12 februari 1646","1559–1646":"1559–1646","1585–1676":"1585–1676","1552–1646":"1552–1646","1646":"1646","1676":"1676","1641":"1641","1585":"1585","1552":"1552","12 February 1646":"12 februari 1646","12 Feb 1646":"12 februari 1646","11 Dec 1552":"11 december 1552","02 Mar 1609":"2 maart 1609","1603":"1603","1559":"1559","Lochinver, Sutherland, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Lochinver, Sutherland, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Edinburgh, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lochinver, Sutherland, Scotland":"Lochinver, Sutherland, Schotland","Kirkland,Kilmairis,Stirling,Ayers, Scottland":"Stirling, Western Australia, Australië","County Donegal, Ireland":"County Donegal, Ierland"},"en":{"11 Dec 1552–12 Feb 1646":"11 December 1552–12 February 1646","1559–1646":"1559–1646","1585–1676":"1585–1676","1552–1646":"1552–1646","1646":"1646","1676":"1676","1641":"1641","1585":"1585","1552":"1552","12 February 1646":"12 February 1646","12 Feb 1646":"12 February 1646","11 Dec 1552":"11 December 1552","02 Mar 1609":"2 March 1609","1603":"1603","1559":"1559","Lochinver, Sutherland, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Lochinver, Sutherland, Scotland, United Kingdom","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Edinburgh, Scotland, United Kingdom","Lochinver, Sutherland, Scotland":"Lochinver, Sutherland, Scotland","Kirkland,Kilmairis,Stirling,Ayers, Scottland":"Stirling, Western Australia, Australia","County Donegal, Ireland":"County Donegal, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Duarte","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Carlos, Jesus, Juan, Jorge, Luis, Ruben, Francisco, Miguel, Raul, Pedro.  Portuguese Joao, Joaquim, Agostinho, Henrique, Paulo, Albano, Almir, Anabela, Ilidio, Ligia, Marcio, Margarida.","Portuguese: from the personal name <i>Duarte</i>, a Portuguese name of uncertain origin taken to be the equivalent of   Edward  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["English and Welsh: from the Middle English personal name <i>Edward</i> (Old English <i>Ēadweard</i>, from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, fortune’ + <i>w(e)ard</i> ‘guard, ward’). The popularity of the personal name was largely due to its being the name of the sainted Anglo-Saxon king Edward the Confessor and of three kings in the 13th–14th centuries."]}]},{"name":"Campbell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Camble","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Campbel","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Cambell","meanings":["(1997: 229;2007: 1415; 2010: NA)","Scottish: variant of   Campbell  ."]},{"name":"Campell","meanings":["(2007: 398; 2010: NA)","Scottish (Lanarkshire) and English: variant of   Campbell   (see also   Camel  )."]},{"name":"Beauchamp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."]},{"name":"Camel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Napoleon, Patrice.","English (of Norman origin) and French: nickname from Norman French <i>came(i)l</i> ‘camel’ (from Latin <i>camelus</i>, classical Greek <i>kamēlos</i>), possibly denoting a clumsy person or someone with long legs. It may also be a topographic or habitational name referring to a house with a sign depicting a camel (although surnames derived from house and inn signs are rare in English); compare 5 below.","English: possibly a habitational name from Queen Camel and West Camel in Somerset, early recorded as <i>Camel(le)</i>, possibly a Celtic name from <i>canto-</i> ‘border, district’ and <i>mēl</i> ‘bare hill’."]}]},{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["‘tendril’ or ‘creeper’, often used in metaphors describing the slender curvature of eyebrows, arms, hair, swords, lightning, and women's bodies."]}]},{"name":"Margarette","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaret","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]},{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretha","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margarethe","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1355925,"age":50,"year":"1603","julianDay":2306544,"description":"Accession of James I. Surrender of Hugh O'Neill. Enforcement of English Law in Ireland.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1355926,"age":88,"year":"1641","julianDay":2320424,"description":"Great Catholic-Gaelic rebellion for return of lands, later joined by Old English Catholics in Ireland. Under leadership of Irish chieftain, Rory O'More, conspiracy was formed to seize Dublin and expel the English. English settlers were driven out of Ulster. Catholics hold 59% of land in Ireland.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Margarette Duarte Campbell was born on 11 December 1552, in Lochinver, Sutherland, Scotland. She married Patrick Cunningham on 2 March 1609, in Edinburgh, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 12 February 1646, in County Donegal, Ireland, at the age of 93."},"et":{"11 Dec 1552–12 Feb 1646":"11. detsember 1552–12. veebruar 1646","1559–1646":"1559–1646","1585–1676":"1585–1676","1552–1646":"1552–1646","1646":"1646","1676":"1676","1641":"1641","1585":"1585","1552":"1552","12 February 1646":"12. veebruar 1646","12 Feb 1646":"12. veebruar 1646","11 Dec 1552":"11. detsember 1552","02 Mar 1609":"2. märts 1609","1603":"1603","1559":"1559","Lochinver, Sutherland, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Lochinver, Sutherland, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Edinburgh, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Lochinver, Sutherland, Scotland":"Lochinver, Sutherland, Scotland","Kirkland,Kilmairis,Stirling,Ayers, Scottland":"Stirling, Western Australia, Austraalia","County Donegal, Ireland":"County Donegal, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"11 Dec 1552–12 Feb 1646":"11. joulukuuta 1552–12. helmikuuta 1646","1559–1646":"1559–1646","1585–1676":"1585–1676","1552–1646":"1552–1646","1646":"1646","1676":"1676","1641":"1641","1585":"1585","1552":"1552","12 February 1646":"12. helmikuuta 1646","12 Feb 1646":"12. helmikuuta 1646","11 Dec 1552":"11. joulukuuta 1552","02 Mar 1609":"2. maaliskuuta 1609","1603":"1603","1559":"1559","Lochinver, Sutherland, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Lochinver, Sutherland, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland, United King